  <billdetail>
    <title>Mauao Historic Reserve Vesting Bill</title>
    <billtype>Government Bill</billtype>
    <repnote>As reported from the Māori Affairs Committee</repnote>
    <commentary id="DLM1248700" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" bill.no="179" bill.type="government" stage="2" year="2008">
      <heading>Commentary</heading>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Recommendation</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Māori Affairs Committee has examined the Mauao Historic Reserve Vesting Bill and recommends that it be passed with the amendments shown.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Introduction</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Mauao Historic Reserve Vesting Bill gives effect to an agreement signed by the Crown, Ngāi Te Rangi, Ngāti Ranginui, Ngāti Pūkenga, the trustees of the Mauao Trust, and Waitaha, in August 2007. The bill provides for the transfer of the fee simple estate in the Mauao historic reserve, known as Mount Maunganui or Mauao, from the Crown to the trustees of the Mauao Trust, to hold on trust for Ngāi Te Rangi, Ngāti Ranginui, and Ngāti Pūkenga.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Because the Reserves Act 1977 does not provide for a transfer of this nature, enabling legislation is necessary. The transfer recognises the special significance of Mauao to tangata whenua in Tauranga Moana. The bill provides that Mauao will continue to be a historic reserve subject to the Reserves Act 1977, which protects Mauao from commercialisation or alienation. As agreed with the parties, the bill also preserves the existing management arrangements for Mauao. The bill does not form part of a Treaty settlement but is intended to help build healthy relationships between the Crown, Tauranga Moana Iwi, and Waitaha.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>In our examination of the bill, we considered the precise nature of the return of the land as expressed in clause 7 of the bill, and the continued joint management of the reserve by the Mauao Trust and the Tauranga City Council.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Ownership rights and obligations</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend that clauses 7 and 8 of the bill be deleted, and that new clause 8 incorporate the intent of clause 7.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We received a significant number of submissions in opposition to clause 7. Most of them expressed concern that the clause does not provide for the return of full ownership of Mauao to iwi, and that the wording of the clause is offensive, implying that the return of the land is in name only, with all other rights remaining with the Crown. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Mauao has the status of a historic reserve under the Reserves Act 1977. Mauao comprises three parcels of land, which are Crown land in respect of which the Crown or the Minister of Conservation has certain powers, duties, and obligations. The Minister of Conservation’s powers include a power to appoint an administering body to manage and control the reserve subject to the provisions of the Reserves Act 1977. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>A clause is required in the bill to ensure, as the agreement to introduce vesting legislation provides, that all general law continues to apply to Mauao after the vesting. The aim of the clause is that the rights and obligations under, for example, health and safety, building, and rating liability legislation, should continue to be the responsibilities of the Crown. However, the Crown cannot know what laws may be passed in the future that may affect the owners of Mauao by creating further rights and obligations. Under the current provision in the bill, the Mauao Trust trustees will not bear any of these present or future ownership obligations. If clause 7 is removed entirely, significant legal uncertainty will arise concerning what obligations the trustees may bear, and what rights they may have as owners of Mauao.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recognise the offence caused by the original wording of clause 7, and therefore recommend that the expression of the intent of the clause be re-worded in clause 8 to address this concern. We also recommend that consequential amendments be made to clause 5, providing that section 5 is subject to section 8, and to clause 10, so it takes account of the deletion of clause 7.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Minor amendments</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend an amendment to the definition of Mauao historic reserve in clause 3, to include the information that Mauao was declared to be a historic reserve by <emphasis style="italic">Gazette</emphasis> notice 1981 Vol III, p. 3065. We also recommend that a consequential amendment be made to the description of the reserve in Schedule 1.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend that clause 15(1) be amended to require the Minister of Māori Affairs to comply with subsections (2) and (3), rather than the Minister of Conservation, as the Minister of Māori Affairs has agreed to undertake the application for the computer freehold register. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend that Schedule 2 be amended to provide details of the encumbrances to the Mauao historic reserve, so the bill can more accurately reflect the rights held by the Tauranga City Council.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Joint management of Mauao historic reserve</heading>
        <para>
          <text>A number of submitters commented on the issue of joint management of Mauao historic reserve by the Tauranga City Council and Tauranga Moana iwi, some recommending that the bill be amended to provide for the joint management of Mauao by the council and iwi.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We note that a memorandum of understanding has been agreed between the Tauranga City Council and Tauranga Moana iwi, which reflects the iwi’s aspirations regarding Mauao. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Joint management of Mauao historic reserve is outside the scope of the vesting agreement and the bill. Under the Reserves Act 1977, the Minister of Conservation has the power to appoint the administering body of Mauao historic reserve. This provision could be used to include the trustees of the Mauao Trust in the future. We note that this was not contemplated in drafting the bill because it was outside the scope of the negotiated agreement. As the memorandum of understanding is not a legally binding document, it is not appropriate that such an agreement should be included in legislation.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.appendix>
        <heading>Appendix</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee process</heading>
          <para>
            <text>The Mauao Historic Reserve Vesting Bill was referred to the committee on 11 December 2007. The closing date for submissions was 15 February 2008. We received and considered 27 submissions from interested groups and individuals. We heard 17 submissions, at hearings in Wellington and Tauranga.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We received advice from Te Puni Kōkiri.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee membership</heading>
          <para>
            <text>Dave Hereora (Chairperson)</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Dr Pita Sharples (Deputy Chairperson)</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Chris Finlayson</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Tau Henare</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Mahara Okeroa</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Pita Paraone</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Mita Ririnui</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Georgina te Heuheu</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text/>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.appendix>
    </commentary>
